06262nam a22010215i 9781512825220DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815128252207 a10.9783/97815128252202doi  a(DE-B1597)650959  a(OCoLC)1415805844  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0350102bisacsh  aMS 36002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123685:1 aCabot, Heath, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn the Doorstep of Europe :bAsylum and Citizenship in Greece /cHeath Cabot. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the 2023 Edition. Seeking Refuge -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. The Rock of Judgment -- tACT I. Governance -- t1. European Moral Geographies -- t2. Documenting Legal Limbo -- tACT II. Judgment -- t3. Engaging Tragedy -- t4. Images of Vulnerability -- t5. Recognizing the Real Refugee -- tACT III. Citizenship -- t6. Rearticulating the Ethnos -- t7. Citizens of Athens -- tThe Machine -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the global financial crisis of 2008, Greece has shouldered a heavy burden struggling with internal political and financial insecurity as well as hosting enormous numbers of migrants and asylum seekers who arrive by land and sea. In On the Doorstep of Europe, Heath Cabot presents an ethnographic study of the asylum system in Greece, tracing the ways asylum seekers, bureaucrats, and service providers attempt to navigate the dilemmas of governance, ethics, knowledge, and social relations that emerge through this legal process. Centering on the work of an asylum advocacy NGO in Athens, Cabot explores how workers and clients grapple with predicaments endemic to Europeanization and rights-based protection. Drawing inspiration from classical Greek tragedy to highlight both the transformative potential and violence of law, Cabot charts the structural violence effected through European governance, rights frameworks, and humanitarian intervention while also exploring how Greek society is being remade from the inside out. She shows how, in contemporary Greece, relationships between insiders and outsiders are radically reconfigured through legal, political, and economic crises.Now updated with a preface reflecting on the critical stakes of the book’s exploration of refuge in light of events that have transpired in and beyond Europe since its initial publication, On the Doorstep of Europe highlights how border crossers and residents in countries of arrival navigate legal and political violence. Cabot’s on-the-ground account of asylum and immigration in Europe’s borderlands, based on fieldwork conducted between 2004 and 2011, shows how the difficulties encountered by asylum seekers in an earlier time remain relevant and revealing in the face of ongoing crises and challenges today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAsylum, Right ofzGreece2DLC. 0aCitizenshipzGreece2DLC. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzGreece2DLC. 0aLegal assistance to refugeeszGreece2DLC. 0aPolitical refugeesxLegal status, laws, etczGreece2DLC. 0aSocial work with immigrantszGreece2DLC. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aAsylum.  aAthens Refugee Services.  aAthens.  aEthnography.  aEuropean Union.  aGreece.  aNGO.  aTheory.  aactivisim.  aadvocacy.  aasylum claims.  aasylum seekers.  aborder studies.  aborderlands.  abureaucracy bureaucratic.  acitizenship.  aentitlement.  aglobalization.  agovernance.  